;################################################### COMMODITY
@Node "3_Commodity" "Usage / Commodity"

                            @{b}ÀCÀOÀMÀMÀOÀDÀIÀTÀYÀ@{ub}

  @{i}TP@{ui}  tries to install itself as a commodity.  Look at the @{"About window" link "3_AboutWindow"} to
  see if @{i}TP@{ui} could install itself as a commodity, or not.

  You  can  partly  control  @{i}TP@{ui}  with  the  Exchange  program  (comes with
  Workbench).  Here's how the buttons affect @{i}TP@{ui} :


  @{fg shine}TPs HOTKEY@{fg text}    : ctrl + lshift + t
                  This brings @{i}TP@{ui}'s window to the front of all
                  the windows on the current screen.

  @{fg shine}SHOW INTERFACE@{fg text}: This will put @{i}TP@{ui} into "Big GUI" mode.
  @{fg shine}HIDE INTERFACE@{fg text}: This will put @{i}TP@{ui} into "Small GUI" mode.
  @{fg shine}INACTVE/ACTIVE@{fg text}: This  doesn't  do  anything at the moment.
                  If  anyone  has  got  any  suggestions as
                  what these can do, then please contact me.
  @{fg shine}REMOVE@{fg text}        : This will make @{i}TP@{ui} quit. Basically.


  When I was designing @{i}TP@{ui}'s Preferences window, I forgot about making @{i}TP@{ui}'s
  hoykey  configurable.   Sorry.   I'll implement this in a later version.
  Also,  if  you've  got  any ideas for what I can use the Hotkey function
  for, then contact me.
@EndNode

;################################################### AREXX
@Node "3_ARexx" "Usage / ARexx"

                                @{b}ÀAÀRÀEÀXÀXÀ@{ub}

  @{i}Trinity  Player@{ui} has an extensive range of ARexx commands which allows it
  to control other programs and be controlled by other programs. There are
  80 ARexx commands in this version.

  For example, you can use a program like Scala (I'm not sure if it has an
  ARexx port - even though I've got Scala!) to start the current CD in the
  CD  drive playing when it gets to a certain effect.  By using @{i}TP@{ui}'s ARexx
  port,  you  can  write your own program (with any language that lets you
  use  ARexx  ports)  that  gets details such as the CD's track times, the
  CD's  title/artist/track  list/etc  or  whatever from @{i}Trinity Player@{ui} and
  then  insert  them into your program!  Thus creating a new interface for
  @{i}TP@{ui}  to  use!   For example, you can hide @{i}TP@{ui}'s GUI and use your new GUI -
  which  could  be small and compact and require a standard HiRes 4-colour
  screen!  Basically, you can do pretty much anything you want!

                               @{fg shine}@{bg fill}@{" AREXX COMMANDS " link "3_AREXX_MENU"}@{fg text}@{bg background}
@EndNode

@Node "3_AREXX_MENU" "AREXX COMMANDS MENU"

                            @{fg shine}À@{fg text}@{b}AREXX COMMANDS MENU@{ub}@{fg shine}À@{fg text}

  All parameters with a @{fg fill}@{b}<@{fg text}@{ub} and @{fg fill}@{b}>@{ub}@{fg text} are required.
  All parameters with a @{fg fill}@{b}[@{fg text}@{ub} and @{fg fill}@{b}]@{ub}@{fg text} are optional.

    @{fg shine}@{b}@{u}INFORMATION@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
       @{"      CD      " link "AREXX_INFO_CD"}@{"    WINDOW    " link "AREXX_INFO_Window"}@{"    SCREEN    " link "AREXX_INFO_Screen"}@{"   PROGRAM    " link "AREXX_INFO_Program"}
       @{" PREFERENCES  " link "AREXX_INFO_Prefs"}@{"     MISC     " link "AREXX_INFO_Misc"}

    @{fg shine}@{b}@{u}CONTROLLING@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
       @{"      CD      " link "AREXX_CONT_CD"}@{"    WINDOW    " link "AREXX_CONT_Window"}@{"  REQUESTERS  " link "AREXX_CONT_Requesters"}

@EndNode

;--------------------------------------------------- AREXX COMMANDS

@Node "AREXX_INFO_CD" "ARexx / Information / CD"

                               @{b}@{u}CD INFORMATION@{ub}@{uu}

  @{b}CD_TITLE@{ub}
    This returns the CD's title.
     eg. @{fg shine}The Best Of Belinda Carlisle #1@{fg text}

  @{b}CD_ARTIST@{ub}
    This returns the artist/band of the CD.
     eg. @{fg shine}Belinda Carlisle@{fg text}

  @{b}TRACK@{ub}
    This returns the current Track (either being played, paused
    or whatever). This still returns the Track number even if
    the CD is stopped.
     eg. @{fg shine}6@{fg text}

  @{b}SONG_NAME@{ub}
    This returns the title of the current track.
     eg. @{fg shine}Summer Rain@{fg text}

  @{b}TRACK_TIME@{ub}
    This will return the track's elapsed time.
     eg. @{fg shine}01:34@{fg text}  (@{i}@{u}always@{uu} a 5 digit string@{ui})

  @{b}TRACK_REMAINING@{ub}
    This will return the time remaining in the current track.
    NOTE: Everytime you call this, the Track's remaining time will
          be re-calculated.
     eg. @{fg shine}02:09@{fg text}  (@{i}@{u}always@{uu} a 5 digit string@{ui})

  @{b}DISC_TIME@{ub}
    This will return the total combined track times of the
    entire CD.
     eg. @{fg shine}62:28@{fg text}  (@{i}@{u}always@{uu} a 5 digit string@{ui})

  @{b}INFO_CD_PLAYING@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   CD is in Play mode.
        0   =   CD is not playing (not in Play mode).

  @{b}INFO_PAUSE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   CD is in Pause mode.
        0   =   CD is not paused (not in Pause mode).

  @{b}INFO_CD_OKAY@{ub}
    Sorry, but I'm not sure what this is supposed to return
    (haha! I NEVER plan my projects! Hahaha). Generally, if
    CD_OKAY=0, then don't try playing a CD, coz there might
    not be a CD in the drive,  or  the CD drive couldn't be
    intialised (SCSI Unit/Device is wrong/etc) or something.
    Returns:
        1   =   The CD drive is ready to play a CD.
        0   =   There's something wrong (no CD in drive/etc)

  @{b}INFO_SHUFFLE_MODE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Shuffle Mode is enabled  (the Shuffle light is on).
        0   =   Shuffle Mode is disabled (the Shuffle light is off).

  @{b}INFO_REPEAT_MODE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Repeat Mode is enabled  (the Repeat light is on).
        0   =   Repeat Mode is disabled (the Repeat light is off).

  @{b}INFO_PREVIEW_MODE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Preview Mode is enabled  (the Preview light is on).
        0   =   Preview Mode is disabled (the Preview light is off).

  @{b}INFO_PROGRAM_MODE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Program Mode is enabled  (the Program light is on).
        0   =   Program Mode is disabled (the Program light is off).
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_INFO_Window" "ARexx / Information / Window"

                                @{b}@{u}WINDOW INFO@{ub}@{uu}

  @{b}WINDOW_TYPE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   The window is currently in BigGUI mode.
        0   =   The window is currently in SmallGUI mode.

  @{b}WINDOW_X@{ub}
    This returns the X co-ordinate window position.
     eg. @{fg shine}118@{fg text}

  @{b}WINDOW_Y@{ub}
    This returns the Y co-ordinate window position
     eg. @{fg shine}64@{fg text}

  @{b}WINDOW_ADDRESS@{ub}
    This returns the main window's address in memory.
    The return value is in decimal.

  @{b}SMALLGUI_X@{ub}
    This returns the X co-ordinate of the Small GUI
    (or last position if currently in BigGUI mode).

  @{b}SMALLGUI_Y@{ub}
    This returns the Y co-ordinate of the Small GUI
    (or last position if currently in BigGUI mode).

  @{b}SONGED_X@{ub}
    This returns the X co-ordinate of the Song
    Editor's window.

  @{b}SONGED_Y@{ub}
    This returns the Y co-ordinate of the Song
    Editor's window.

  @{b}PROGED_X@{ub}
    This returns the X co-ordinate of the Program
    Editor's window.

  @{b}PROGED_Y@{ub}
    This returns the Y co-ordinate of the Program
    Editor's window.

  @{b}PREFS_WINX@{ub}
    This returns the X co-ordinate of the prefs window.

  @{b}PREFS_WINY@{ub}
    This returns the Y co-ordinate of the prefs window.
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_INFO_Screen" "ARexx / Information / Screen"

                                @{b}@{u}SCREEN INFO@{ub}@{uu}

  @{b}SCREEN_FONT_NAME@{ub}
    This returns the current screen's font name.
     eg. @{fg shine}personal.font@{fg text}

  @{b}SCREEN_FONT_SIZE@{ub}
    This will return the Y size of the screen's
    current font.
     eg. @{fg shine}8@{fg text}

  @{b}SCREEN_TITLE@{ub}
    This will return the title of current screen.
     eg. @{fg shine}Trinity Player V0.70@{fg text}

  @{b}SCREEN_DEFAULTTITLE@{ub}
    This returns the default title of the current screen.
     eg. @{fg shine}Workbench@{fg text}

  @{b}SCREEN_ADDRESS@{ub}
    This will return the current  screen's  structure
    address in memory. The return value is in decimal.

  @{b}SCREEN_WIDTH@{ub}
    This will return the current screen's width
    in pixels.
     eg. @{fg shine}640@{fg text}

  @{b}SCREEN_HEIGHT@{ub}
    This will return the current screen's height
    in pixels.
     eg. @{fg shine}512@{fg text}

  @{b}SCREEN_DISPLAY@{ub}
    Returns:
        0   =   The current screen is PAL.
       -1   =   The current screen is NTSC (yuk!).

  @{b}SCREEN_FLAGS@{ub}
    This will return the screen's current flag settings.
    I dunno what format the settings are off the top of
    my head.  I suppose you better look at some include
    files or something. Don't know really.

  @{b}SCREEN_BARHEIGHT@{ub}
    This returns the height of the title bar of the
    current screen (normally 11 with an 8-point font).

  @{b}SCREEN_MouseX@{ub}
    This returns the X position of the mouse.

  @{b}SCREEN_MouseY@{ub}
    This returns the Y position of the mouse.
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_INFO_Program" "ARexx / Information / Program"

                                @{b}@{u}PROGRAM INFO@{ub}@{uu}

  @{b}COMMODITY@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   @{i}TP@{ui} is running as a commodity.
        0   =   @{i}TP@{ui} failed to install itself as a commodity.

  @{b}AREXX_PORTNAME@{ub}
    This returns the name of @{i}TP@{ui}'s ARexx port. Useless,
    but who cares?
     eg. @{fg shine}TP.1@{fg text}

  @{b}AREXX_PORT@{ub}
    Again, this is useless, but ...
    Returns:
       -1   =   @{i}TP@{ui} was able to install it's ARexx port.
        0   =   @{i}TP@{ui} was unable to install it's ARexx port.

  @{b}VERSION@{ub}
    This returns the version of @{i}Trinity Player@{ui}  that
    is currently running, as a string. If there is a
    U character at the end of the string,  then that
    means that an  Unregistered  version  of  @{i}TP@{ui}  is
    running.  An R character means that a Registered
    version of @{i}TP@{ui} is running.
     eg. @{fg shine}1.00R@{fg text}
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_INFO_Misc" "ARexx / Information / Miscellaneous"

                             @{b}@{u}MISCELLANEOUS INFO@{ub}@{uu}

  @{b}TIME@{ub}
    This returns the system's current time in 24 hour format.
     eg. @{fg shine}11:42:39@{fg text} (@{i}@{u}always@{uu} an 8 digit string@{ui})

  @{b}QUIT@{ub}
    Obviously, this will make @{i}TP@{ui} quit. A value of 1 is always
    returned.
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_INFO_Prefs" "ARexx / Information / Preferences"

                              @{b}@{u}PREFERENCES INFO@{ub}@{uu}

  @{b}PLAY_INSERTED@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Play Inserted is enabled.
        0   =   Play Inserted is disabled.

  @{b}UPDATE_RATE@{ub}
    This returns the Update Rate set in the preferences.

  @{b}UPDATE_POS@{ub}
    This returns the value the Update Rate counter is currently
    at.  This  value increases by 1 every vertical blank and is
    reset when it gets to the Update Rate.

  @{b}CLOCK@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   The clock is enabled.
        0   =   The clock is disabled.

  @{b}ASK_OVERWRITE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Ask Overwrite is enabled.
        0   =   Ask Overwrite is disabled.

  @{b}POP_TO_FRONT@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Pop To Front is enabled.
        0   =   Pop To Front is disabled.

  @{b}PLAY_MODE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   End Of Track mode selected.
        0   =   End Of CD    mode selected.

  @{b}DISCS_PATH@{ub}
    This returns a string containing the path of where
    the CD ID files will be saved.
     eg. @{fg shine}DH1:Utilitites/TrinityPlayer/Discs/@{fg text}

  @{b}PUBLIC_SCREEN@{ub}
    This returns a string of where @{i}TP@{ui} should open it's
    window (if enabled).
     eg. @{fg shine}Workbench@{fg text}

  @{b}START_FROM_TRACK@{ub}
    This returns the Track number that's in the preferences
    regarding the first track that should be played if this
    mode is enabled.

  @{b}PREVIEW_DELAY@{ub}
    This  returns the Preview Delay value in seconds.

  @{b}SCSI_DEVICE@{ub}
    This will return the device entered in the SCSI
    DEVICE string in the prefs.
     eg. @{fg shine}squirrelscsi.device@{fg text}

  @{b}SCSI_UNIT@{ub}
    This will return the unit number of the SCSI
    device.
     eg. @{fg shine}1@{fg text}
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_CONT_CD" "ARexx / Control / CD"

                                 @{b}CONTROL CD@{ub}

  @{b}STOP@{ub}
    This will stop playing the current CD.

  @{b}PLAYTRACK@{ub} @{fg shine}<Track>@{fg text}
    This will play the specified Track.  Remember,  check
    to see if everything is okay first (@{"CD INFO" link "AREXX_INFO_CD"}).
    The way the track will be played (until end of  track
    or CD) depends on the Play Mode set in the prefs.
    A  return  value of 1 means that the track started to
    play okay. A value of 0 means that an error occurred.
    If you do try to play a track when something is wrong
    (no CD in drive/etc),  then  you'll  just  get 0 as a
    result - @{i}TP@{ui} will not crash (`be stupid if it did).

  @{b}PAUSE@{ub}
    This will pause the CD  if  it's  playing.  A  return
    value of 1 means that the CD is paused,  a value of 0
    means that the CD is not paused (playing/stopped).
    To un-pause,  just  call  this command again and note
    the return result.

  @{b}REWIND@{ub} @{fg shine}<Seconds>@{fg text}
    This is the number of seconds the  currently  playing
    track should be rewound. No return result.

  @{b}FORWARD@{ub} @{fg shine}<Seconds>@{fg text}
    This is the opposite of REWIND,  as it  goes  forward
    the specified numbers of <Seconds>. No return result.

  @{b}EJECT@{ub}
    This will try to eject the CD in the drive.  A  value
    is returned.  Not sure what it is, as I haven't tried
    to find out!  :)

  @{b}CLOSE_CDDA@{ub}
    This will free  all  memory  and  related  structures
    required for operating the CD drive.  @{u}@{b}DO  NOT@{uu}@{ub} use any
    of the above commands after you've used this command.
    If you do try one of the above commands  after  using
    the CLOSE_CDDA command,  you'll  hang  the  computer.
    A value is returned - like above - I'm not sure what.
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_CONT_Window" "ARexx / Control / Window"

                               @{b}CONTROL WINDOW@{ub}

  @{b}WINDOW_BIG@{ub}
    This will put @{i}TP@{ui} into BigGUI mode.

  @{b}WINDOW_SMALL@{ub}
    This will put @{i}TP@{ui} into SmallGUI mode.

  @{b}WINDOW_TITLE@{ub} @{fg shine}<Window Title$> <Screen Title$>@{fg text}
    This lets you change the window/screen title(s).
    Say for example, you just want to change the Screen
    Title, you must put -1 as the Window Title. This stops
    the Window Title being changed. This also works the
    other way round.
    @{u}NOTE@{uu}: If you use this command while @{i}TP@{ui} is in SmallGUI
          mode,  then  it'll  be  changed almost straight
          away. That's because the CD times/etc are being
          displayed in the screen's titlebar.  Unless  of
          course there's no CD playing.

  @{b}DEFAULT_WINDOW_TITLE@{ub}
    If you've changed the window/screen title(s) and you want
    to change them back,  then you can use this command which
    will revert the titles back to the default strings$.

  @{b}MOVE_WINDOW_REL@{ub} @{fg shine}<X delta> <Y delta>@{fg text}
    This will move @{i}TP@{ui}'s main window relative to it's current
    position.  For example, if the window's current position
    is 104 and you give a X value of -3,  then the  window's
    new X position will be 101. A value of 3 will change the
    new X position to 107. Simple really.

  @{b}MOVE_WINDOW_ABS@{ub} @{fg shine}<X> <Y>@{fg text}
    This will move @{i}TP@{ui}'s window to absolute co-ordinates.
    So,  if you pass X as 34 and Y as 63,  then  the  window
    will move to them exact co-ordinates.
    @{b}WARNING:@{ub} If you give wrong values, you can cause @{i}TP@{ui}
             to  quit  with  an  error,  or most likely
             cause a GURU. Not very nice, mista.
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_CONT_Requesters" "ARexx / Control / Requesters"

                             @{b}CONTROL REQUESTERS@{ub}

  @{b}REQUESTER@{ub} @{fg shine}<Title$> <Bodytext$> <GadgetText$>@{fg text}
    This will bring up a (EasyRequest) requester that can
    be used to notify the user, or can be used for a multiple
    choice question or summat.

        @{fg shine}Title$@{fg text}      =   This is what should be in the title
                        bar of the requester.
        @{fg shine}BodyText$@{fg text}   =   This is what should be in the  main
                        body of the requester. You can have
                        more than one line,  by  putting  a
                        Carriage Return (ASCII Char 10)  at
                        the end of each line.
        @{fg shine}GadgetText$@{fg text} =   This  is  what  should  be  in  the
                        button(s).  If you want to give the
                        user more than 1 choice,  then  you
                        must use the | pipe  character  in-
                        between each choice.

        eg.  REQUESTER 'Title!' 'How old are you?' '15|18|21|25+'

    Result: The right-most button will always return a value of 0,
            and for every extra choice,  add  a  value of 1 to the
            next-up right button.  Shit, it's too hard to explain,
            here's an example:

   REQUESTER 'Title!' 'Where do you live?' 'UK|AUSTRAILA|NEW ZEALAND'
                                            |       |          |
                                     .------'     .-'          !
                                  Returns 1    Returns 2    Returns 0

  If  you  were to put 'UK|AUSTRIALIA|MY RECTUM|NEW ZEALAND', and the user
  clicked on "MY RECTUM", then the return result would be 3.  Because it's
  the 3rd one to the right.

       @{i}Don't blame me for the way this works, it's Commodores' fault!@{ui}


  @{b}GETTEXT@{ub} @{fg shine}<Title$> <Default> <Action>@{fg text}
    You can get a string/integer from the user by using this command.

        @{fg shine}Title$@{fg text}  =   This is what should be displayed to the user.
                    Only one line allowed - and don't make it too long!

        @{fg shine}Default@{fg text} =   If you're using the STRING action (see below), then
                    this  is  the string that will appear in the string
                    gadget.  If you're using the INTEGER  action,  then
                    this is the numerical value that'll appear  in  the
                    integer gadget.

        @{fg shine}Action@{fg text}  =   This determines the type of input you require  from
                    the user.  STRING will let alpha-numeric characters
                    and INTEGER will only allow numerical characters to
                    be entered.

    Result: The entered string/value will be returned. If the user
            doesn't enter anything, then nothing will be returned.
@EndNode

